Interface ComparableSet

  • All Superinterfaces:
    java.lang.Cloneable, java.util.Collection<java.lang.Comparable>, java.lang.Comparable, java.lang.Iterable<java.lang.Comparable>, java.util.Set<java.lang.Comparable>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    ComparableHashSet, ComparableTreeSet, HybridSet

    public interface ComparableSet
extends java.util.Set<java.lang.Comparable>, java.lang.Comparable, java.lang.Cloneable
    This interface extends the Set interface and implements the Comparable interface. All elements inserted into a ComparableSet must be Comparable objects that are mutually comparable. That means, for all elements e1 and e2 in the ComparableSet, the call e1.compareTo(e2) must not throw an exception.

    Furthermore, the ordering must be consistent with equals. (For a precise definition of consistent with equals see the Comparable interface.) In addition, an object must not be mutated while it is an element of a ComparableSet.

    Note that implementations of this interface may further restrict which elements may be added to the set. In addition, write protection can be activated in order to turn the ComparableSet into an unmodifiable set. Any attempt to change the contents of an unmodifiable set will cause an exception to be thrown.

    Note that although the elements must be Comparable objects, there are no guarantees concerning the order in which the elements are returned by the iterator obtained when calling the iterator() method.

    Two instances of ComparableSet can be mutually compared if all elements contained in the sets are mutually comparable.

    This is the definition of lexical ordering. If two sets are different then the disjunction of those two sets is not empty. Let k be the smallest element in that disjunction. Then the set not containing k lexically precedes the other set.

    Thus, a subset always lexically precedes its superset. However, the converse is not true, i.e. the lexically smaller set is not always a subset of a set that is lexically greater.

    • Method Detail

      • clone

        java.lang.Object clone()
        Creates and returns a copy of this ComparableSet.

        The purpose of this method is to create a copy of a ComparableSet that is an instance of the same class as the original object.

        If it is not necessary that the copy is an instance of the same class it is recommended not to use this method but a constructor of a class that implements java.util.Collection instead. For example, a copy of the ComparableSet cs can be created using Set copy = new HashSet(cs) rather than Set copy = cs.clone() if the copy does not need to be a ComparableSet object.

        Returns:
        a copy of this instance that is not write protected.
        See Also:
        Collection

      • disallowChanges

        boolean disallowChanges()
        Activates write protection on this set.

        After this method has been called, this set shall be unmodifiable, i.e. if there is a call attempting to change the contents of this set, an exception will be thrown.

        Returns:
        true iff write protection is activated.

      • compareTo

        int compareTo(java.lang.Object anotherSet)
        Compares two ComparableSet objects lexically.

        This is the definition of lexical ordering. If two sets are different then the disjunction of those two sets is not empty. Let k be the smallest element in that disjunction. Then the set not containing k lexically precedes the other set.

        Thus, a subset always lexically precedes its superset. However, the converse is not true, i.e. the lexically smaller set is not always a subset of a set that is lexically greater.

        Specified by:
        compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable
        Parameters:
        anotherSet - the ComparableSet to be compared.
        Returns:
        the value 0 if the argument set is equal to this set; a value less than zero if this set is lexically smaller than the argument set; a value greater than zero if this set is lexically greater than the argument set.
